<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOVIET TRADE UNIONS TO GET RIGHT TO STRIKE UNDER DRAFT LAW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Soviet trade unions, long closely controlled by Communist authorities, will be 
given the right to strike under a draft law to be adopted in the next few 
months, union leader Stepan Shalayev said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
The draft law follows sporadic reports from across the country of wildcat 
strikes by miners, bus drivers and carpet weavers demanding better pay and 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
Leningrad police officers demonstrated in the city center April 9 to back a 
series of demands, according to the newspaper Socialist Industry. 
</P>
<P>
Stoppages linked with nationalist unrest have paralyzed industry in Georgia, 
Armenia and Azerbaijan several times in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
"The right (to strike) is being considered a means to press management to speed 
up the resolution of labor disputes," Shalayev said in an interview with the 
trade union paper Trud. 
</P>
<P>
"But it is an extreme measure which should be applied only in exceptional 
cases," he added. 
</P>
<P>
The draft law says: "A trade union committee . . . has the right to stop work 
at an enterprise in an organization when the procedure, established by law, of 
considering a labor dispute is being violated or when management does not live 
up to an agreement that has been reached." 
</P>
</TEXT>
